The netron screenshot showing no input to the ConstantOfShape node is because the input is an initializer and not the output from another node. This is perfectly valid. 

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/979079/138029632-85b118d6-272a-482f-a88b-abef81c15710.png)

> --cmake_extra_defines ONNXRUNTIME_VERSION=1.8.2

That commit id is for 1.9.0. To make things clearer maybe do `git checkout rel-1.9.0` (should equate to the same commit id) and remove `--cmake_extra_defines ONNXRUNTIME_VERSION=1.8.2 CMAKE_CUDA_ARCHITECTURES=86` from your build command as I'm not aware of any reason why you'd need those.

It would also be good to validate you can load the model with the official ORT 1.9 python package, as I'm able to do that. 

`pip3 install onnxruntime`  and....

```python
import onnxruntime as ort
session = ort.InferenceSession('<path to>/faster_dianlan3.onnx')
```

You should see a number of messages about initializers in graph inputs preventing optimizations, but the session should be able to be created.

Yes, I can load the model with python. I want to do inference using c++ in Ubuntu system, so I build onnxruntime from source. I have chanded onnxruntime version to 1.9.0, CMAKE_CUDA_ARCHITECTURES=86 means I use GeForce 3080 GPU. I build the .cpp file to executable file, the error occurred:
terminate called after throwing an instance of 'Ort::Exception'
what(): Load model from ./faster_dianlan3.onnx failed:This is an invalid model. Error in Node:ConstantOfShape_1085 : No Op registered for ConstantOfShape with domain_version of 11
Aborted (core dumped)
when do inference with the executable file.

Not sure why your build lacks support for ConstantOfShape. Is there a reason why the pre-built package from https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/releases can't be used? There are packages for 1.9.0 and 1.8.1 there (note that for a patch release we only have packages for things affected by the patch). e.g. https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/releases/download/v1.9.0/onnxruntime-linux-x64-gpu-1.9.0.tgz

Yes it does. 

The empty domain string equates to the default onnx domain. When you register a custom op domain using that as the domain, some of the internal checks are thrown off and we can't look up schemas for onnx operators correctly.

What are you trying to do via custom op registration? If you are trying to replace some existing ONNX op with a custom implementation I believe currently you would need to use a custom domain, and update the relevant nodes in the model to have that domain.

e.g. say you wanted to use a custom op for Gemm, the nodes in the model would have domain of "" (i.e. ONNX) and op_type of Gemm. if you have a Gemm operator in your custom ops you would need to update the Gemm nodes in the model to have a domain that matches your custom op domain. 

This is fairly easily done using the onnx python library
```python
import onnx

def add_custom_op_domain_to_gemm_node(node):
    # update relevant nodes to use the kernel from your custom domain
    if node.op_type == 'Gemm':
        node.domain = 'my_domain'

def iterate_graph(graph, per_node_func):

    for node in graph.node:
        per_node_func(node)

        # recurse into subgraph for control flow nodes (Scan/Loop/If)
        for attr in node.attribute:
            if attr.HasField('g'):
                iterate_graph(attr.g, per_node_func)

model = onnx.load('model.onnx')
iterate_graph(model.graph, add_custom_op_domain_to_gemm_node)
onnx.save(model, 'new_model.onnx')
```

Note that that example doesn't recurse into nodes with a graph attribute (Scan/Loop/If) in case that's relevant.

Most likely the error doesn't disappear - the model just fails earlier due to the onnx kernel lookup failure when the domain is empty.

Does the MMCVRoiAlign node in the model have a domain of 'abc'? Should be able to check that using Netron.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/44046955/140017900-ab5fe4f0-ea53-4890-bfa5-07a0c7283247.png)

It seems ok, the module "mmcv" should be the domain, right?

When I use following code:
`Ort::CustomOpDomain custom_op_domain("mmcv");`

both errors disappear.

By the way, where could I look for more details about onnxruntime or how to use onnxruntime.

For the model to load successfully what Netron is calling 'module' must be the domain.

Documentation is at https://onnxruntime.ai/
